      "content": "Your skepticism is understandable in the digital age where privacy concerns are ever-present. Affective computing technologies do have the potential to detect physiological signals, but such data collection would typically require explicit consent from the user. Companies are bound by various regulations, such as GDPR in Europe or CCPA in California, which protect users' rights and require transparency about data collection and usage. If you feel your privacy is being compromised, you can often check your device settings or contact the company directly to inquire about data practices. Remember, it's always within your rights to request information about how your data is used and to opt-out of certain services if you're uncomfortable with the level of monitoring involved.",
